Linear model limitation can represent output of two input that interactive in additive way, but can't represent output of two input that interactives in mutiple way. But why still linear model? As linear operation is really nice and efficient:

  1. Big matrix multiplies are exactly what GPUs were designed for, they are relative cheap and very very fast
  2. Numerically, linear operations are very stable, small change in input can never yield big change in output
  3. The derivatives are very nice too, the derivative of linear function is constant. Numerically constant is stable

Therefore, we would like to keep our parameters inside big linear functions, but we also want the entire model to be non-linear, as we can't just rely our parameters in linear function, as its multiplication would still be a big linear function. We therefore need Non-linearality. Thus we introudce you the lazy engineer's favorite non-linear function : Recitifed Linear Unit (Relu)

Network of ReluÂ¶

Multilayer Neural Networks. In this lesson, you'll learn how to build multilayer neural networks with TensorFlow. Adding a hidden layer to a network allows it to model more complex functions. Also, using a non-linear activation function on the hidden layer lets it model non-linear functions.

We shall learn about ReLU, a non-linear function, or rectified linear unit. The ReLU function is 0 for negative inputs and x for all inputs $x$>0.

Next, you'll see how a ReLU hidden layer is implemented in TensorFlow. Note: Depicted above is a "2-layer" neural network:

  1. The first layer effectively consists of the set of weights and biases applied to X and passed through ReLUs. The output of this layer is fed to the next one, but is not observable outside the network, hence it is known as a hidden layer.
  2. The second layer consists of the weights and biases applied to these intermediate outputs, followed by the softmax function to generate probabilities.

To optimize your model, we apply the input to Forward Prop, then Backward prop. To do this, we need to compute the gradients, to compute the gradients, we use backward prop to calculate, after we get the gradients of each block, i.e. $\Delta w_1$ and $\Delta w_2$, we use gradients with the learning rate $\alpha$ to update the weights of each block, i.e. ($w_1, w_2$).

After assignment 2, we now have a small deep learning model, well it's not that deep, just 1 hidden layer, however, we can increase the size of the hidden nodes to make the model more complex (above meaning making H bigger), but making it bigger is not particularly efficient in general. This is the central idea where deep learning comes into play. Instead of making model more complex, we can add more hidden layers and make our model deeper.

Couple good reason to do that:

  • Parameter efficiency. You can use fewer parameters to train your network by going deeper rather than wider.
  • Reallife problem tend to have hierachy structure which usually deep models captures.

More detail about dropout, a technique that emerges recently years for reguralization. How it works:

  1. The value that go from one layer to the next are often called activations. Now take these activations randomly, for every example you train your network on, set half of them to 0.
  2. Completely and randomly, you basically take half of the data that's following thru your network and just destroy it and then randomly again.
InÂ [15]:
Image(filename='imgs/pic14.jpg')
Out[15]:

So what happen to dropout? Your netowrk can never reply on any given activation to be present, because they might be squashed at any given moment. So it is forced to learn a reduncdant representation for everything to make sure that at least some of the information remains.

One activations get smashed, but there is alaways one or more that do the same job. And that don't get killled. So, everthing remains fine at the end.

3. When you evaluate the network that's been trained with drop out, you obviously dont want the randomness, you want sth deterministic. Instead, you're going to want to take the consensus over these redundant set. You want $y_e$ here to be the average of all the $y_t$s that you got during training.Â¶

Here's a trick to make sure this expectation holds. During training, not only do you use zero out so the activations that you drop out, but you also scale the remaining acvations by a factor of 2. This way, when it comes into average them during evaluation, you just remove these dropouts and scaling operations from your neural net. And the result is an average of these activations that is properly scaled.
